AuthBy

Target IP: 192.168.180.46

Enumeratation and pillaging like bandits in the old country.

Reconnaissance


There are four TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above.


Performing an aggressive nmap scan returns the result above. By the looks of it, the FTP application on port 21 allows anonymous login. There is another FTP application on port 3145. HTTP application is available on port 242. And the RDP is open on port 3389.

Enumeration

Port 21: FTP

This FTP application does not allow me to download anything. I do not have upload permission either. However, I did find the interesting usernames: offsec, anonymous, admin, as shown above. I stored the usernames in a textfile called usernames.

Port 242: HTTP

Browsing to http://192.168.180.46:242/ informs me to login, as shown above. I tried spraying default credentials such as admin:admin, but I had no luck.


Using curl, I tried to identify what type of authentication is being used. As shown above, the WWW-Authenticate field mentions Qui e nuce nuculeum esse volt, frangit nucem! and this translates to He who wants to be a nut from a nut breaks the nut!. Time to enumerate harder.


Using the command hydra -L usernames -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 192.168.180.46 -s 242 http-get, I managed to bruteforce the credentials offsec:elite for this web application. I did not find anything useful when viewing the source-code either.


After logging in using the bruteforced credentials, the webpage above is displayed. However, I feel like I hit a wall as doing a directory search leads to nothing.

Exploitation


After running hydra with the same usernames wordlist against the FTP application on port 21 returned a valid hit for admin:admin. And using this new credentials, I gained access to the files above. I downloaded these files on my machine. The .htpasswd contains the encrypted password which I already bruteforced using hydra.


But I notice this admin user has write permission. So I can upload a PHP shell using the FTP application. I created a simple PHP webshell and uploaded it.


Then I accessed my PHP webshell at http://192.168.180.46:242/shell.php. In the picture above, I sent the command whoami and received the output above. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now.


I used the modified version of PHP Pentest Monkey reverse shell script from this Github link. Using the FTP application, I uploaded this new PHP reverse shell with the name evil_shell.php. I started a listener on port 80, and browsed to http://192.168.180.46:242/evil_shell.php to start the connection. Then I obtained a reverse shell connection on port 80! Now I have a foothold on the target machine with the session as apache user.

Privilege Escalation


systeminfo shows the useful information above. It looks like the target machine is running Windows Server 2008 SP1. But no hotfixes have been applied!


Running whoami /priv shows the privilege SeImpersonatePrivilege is enabled.


Looks like there are multiple ways to gain system access on the machine. I will go with the first method; that is by exploiting the kernel. I downloaded this exploit above on my machine.


Then using the command i686-w64-mingw32-gcc 40564.c -o exp.exe -lws2_32, I compiled the exploit to target the x86 architecture. I transferred this exploit to the target machine via the FTP with admin:admin credentials on port 21.


After transferring the local privilege escalation exploit, I used the command where /r c:\ "exp.exe" to find its location. I found the exploit at c:\wamp\www. Then I ran this executable using the command .\exp.exe to gain nt authority\system access on the target machine. Now I have full access on the target machine :)
